1. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than the existing landing page?¶

Perform Visual Analysis¶

In [50]:
# point plot of time_spent_on_the_page and landing_page
sns.pointplot(data=df, x='time_spent_on_the_page', y='landing_page');

Observation:¶

More time is spent on the new landing page than the existing landing page.

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Let $\mu_1, \mu_2$ be the mean times spent on the old landing page and the new landing page, respectively.

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0:\mu_1=\mu_2$

against the alternate hypothesis

$H_a:\mu_1<\mu_2$

Assumptions:¶

  • Continuous data - the mean time is measured on a continuous scale.
  • Normally distributed populations - the populations are assumed to be normal.
  • Independent populations - Old [Landing Page] time spent on page v. New [Landing Page] time spent on page)
  • Unequal population standard deviations - As the sample standard deviations are different, the population standard deviations may be assumed to be different.
  • Random sampling from the population is assumed.

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

Observation:¶

2-sample Independent t-test

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

= .05

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [59]:
#import the required function
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

# find the p-value
test_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(time_spent_new_page, time_spent_old_page, equal_var = False, alternative = 'greater')
print('The p-value is ', p_value)

The p-value is  0.0001392381225166549

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [60]:
# compare p-value with alpha
if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.0001392381225166549 is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

The mean time spent on the old landing page is not equal to the mean time of the new landing page.

A similar approach can be followed to answer the other questions.

2. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?¶

In [61]:
# visualization comparing the conversion status for the new landing page and the old landing page
pd.crosstab(df['converted'],df['landing_page'],normalize='index').plot(kind="bar", figsize=(6,8),stacked=True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Observations:¶

The old landing page had more people not convert than the old landing page had people convert.

The new landing page had more people convert than not convert.

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Let $p_1,p_2$ be the proportions of the users who visited the old landing page and the new landing page, respectively.

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0:p_1 =p_2$

against the alternative hypothesis

$H_a:p_1 \neq p_2$

Step 2: Select Appropriate Test¶

Observation:¶

Two Proportion Z-test

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

= .05

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [62]:
#total number of user in control group

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [70]:

else:

As the p-value 0.016052616408112556 is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

The proportion of users who visited the old landing page is not equal to the proportion of users who visted the new landing page.

3. Is the conversion and preferred language are independent or related?¶

In [71]:
# visualization comparing the conversion rate status and language preferred
pd.crosstab(df['converted'],df['language_preferred'],normalize='index').plot(kind="bar", figsize=(6,8),stacked=True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Observations:¶

The English landing page had more people convert than not convert.

The French landing page had more people not convert than convert.

The Spanish landing page had almost the same amount of people convert as it had not convert.

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0:$ Conversion status is independent of language preferred.

against the alternate hypothesis

$H_a:$ Conversion status depends on language preferred.

Assumptions:¶

  • Categorical variables - Yes.
  • Expected value of the number of sample observations in each level of the variable is at least 5 - Yes.
  • Random sampling from the population - Yes.

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

Observation:¶

Chi-Square Test for Independence

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

= .05

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [72]:

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [73]:

In [74]:

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [75]:

    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.21298887487543447 is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

We fail to reject the hypothesis that conversion status is independent of language preferred.

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Let $\mu_1, \mu_2, \mu_3$ be the means of language preferred for English, French, and Spanish, respectively.

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0: \mu_1 = \mu_2 = \mu_3$

against the alternative hypothesis

$H_a: $ At least one mean time for language preferred is different from the rest.

Assumptions:¶

Shapiro-Wilk’s test (Normality)¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0:$ 'language_preferred' follows a normal distribution against the alternative hypothesis

$H_a:$ 'language_preferred' does not follow a normal distribution

Levene’s test (Equality of Variance)¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0$: All the population variances are equal against the alternative hypothesis

$H_a$: At least one variance is different from the rest

Step 7: Draw inference¶

Observation:¶

We do not have enough statistical significance to conclude that at least one mean time of a preferred language is different than the rest.

Conclusions:¶

  • It appears as the mean time on a landing page increases, conversion is more likely.
  • The new landing page seems to attract the attention of customers more often than the old landing page.
  • The mean time spent on the new landing page was within 1 minute of one another across all preferred languages.

Business Recommendations:¶

  • Explore further the increased likelihood of conversion based on more time spent on landing page.
  • Analyze the new landing page for features that are converting the customer more often than the old landing page.
  • Analyze the new landing page for features that are engaging the customer fractionally longer than the old landing page.
